mes:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard De Rokele was born about 1252, in Colkirk, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William De Rokele, was 26 and his mother, Mrs William De Rokele, was 23. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Cecilia. He died in 1296, at the age of 45."},"et":{"ABT 1252–1296":"umbes 1252–1296","1252–1296":"1252–1296","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1276–Male":"1276–Surnud","1278–1307":"1278–1307","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1231–Female":"1231–Surnud","1228":"1228","ABT 1252":"umbes 1252","ABT 1276":"umbes 1276","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1231":"1231","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1307":"1307","COLKIRK, NORFOLK, ENGLAND":"Colkirk, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colkirk, Norfolk, England":"Colkirk, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1252–1296":"noin 1252–1296","1252–1296":"1252–1296","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1276–Male":"1276–Kuollut","1278–1307":"1278–1307","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1231–Female":"1231–Kuollut","1228":"1228","ABT 1252":"noin 1252","ABT 1276":"noin 1276","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1231":"1231","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1307":"1307","COLKIRK, NORFOLK, ENGLAND":"Colkirk, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Colkirk, Norfolk, England":"Colkirk, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"ABT 1252–1296":"environ 1252–1296","1252–1296":"1252–1296","1255–Female":"1255–Décédée","1276–Male":"1276–Décédé","1278–1307":"1278–1307","1228–Male":"1228–Décédé","1231–Female":"1231–Décédée","1228":"1228","ABT 1252":"environ 1252","ABT 1276":"environ 1276","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1231":"1231","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1307":"1307","COLKIRK, NORFOLK, ENGLAND":"Colkirk, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Colkirk, Norfolk, England":"Colkirk, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard De Rokele est né environ 1252, à Colkirk, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William De Rokele, avait 26 ans et sa